THE RISK (context, do not rewrite): perturbation [{"nodeId":"obtainableFactor","op":"scale","value":0.5,"note":"Roughly half of window-period fit-out milestones in DE/NL slip beyond the 12-month YAM horizon"}], likelihood 0.45, category exogenous

FIELDS TO REWRITE:
{
 "title": "Frankfurt's 24–36-month grid queue and Amsterdam's 350 MVA cap turn the venture's 12-month window into a delivery trough",
 "narrative": "78% of the modeled TAM sits in Germany and the Netherlands — precisely the two geographies where capacity additions are grid-gated. Frankfurt (60–75% of German capacity) faces 24–36-month grid-connection waits; Amsterdam is at 852 MW with a draft zoning plan capping new connections at 350 MVA until 2030; EMEA-wide, capacity under construction has plateaued at ~2.5 GW despite a 15 GW pipeline. PDU orders land at fit-out milestones, which are gated by energization dates, not by the 9% trend CAGR. If 2026 energizations slip right — and the queue data says many will — Year-1 orders slip with them, regardless of what the market does by 2030.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "Frankfurt carries ~745 MW of IT load with grid connections facing 24–36-month waits; Amsterdam's draft umbrella zoning plan caps new connection capacity at 350 MVA until 2030; EMEA under-construction capacity has plateaued at ~2.5 GW on power and permitting constraints",
   "refs": [
    "digest:geo-DE#c20",
    "digest:geo-NL#c8",
    "digest:geo-NL#c3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Germany (0.50) and the Netherlands (0.28) are 78% of the geographic weight, and Frankfurt alone is 60–75% of the German base — so a grid-driven slip in these two hubs is a slip in most of the venture's addressable fit-out calendar",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:geo.DE",
    "ledger:geo.NL",
    "digest:geo-DE#c1",
    "digest:geo-DE#c4"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The 9% CAGR is a 2030 trend, not a 2026 delivery schedule; YAM is a first-12-months number, so the slip compiles to obtainableFactor (pace), not to the trend node — Year-1 orderable fit-outs shrink even while the long-run TAM is intact",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:shape.cagr",
    "ledger:obtainableFactor",
    "profile:Stage"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "Grid congestion is a known headline, so it appears priced in — but the model prices it nowhere: shape.cagr is a smooth 9% and obtainableFactor is a generic benchmark. The surface appearance of 'strong secular demand' hides that demand in the window is lumpy and gated: pre-let capacity absorbed faster than it can be replaced means orders bunch AFTER energizations, which are exactly what is slipping.",
 "falsifier": "H1-2026 evidence that Frankfurt and Amsterdam energizations are converting on schedule — e.g., JLL/C&W showing under-construction MW moving to live at or above the prior year's conversion rate in both hubs.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "Queue lengths and the 2.5 GW construction plateau are documented in current reporting; offsetting this, some 2026 deliveries already hold secured connections (e.g., Pure DC's 100 MVA private substation in Amsterdam), so a partial rather than total slip is the modal outcome. [evidence revision: Constraint premises are more strongly and consistently corroborated than the base hypothesis assumed (Statista lead times far exceed the 24-36 month figure cited; Mainova says mid-2030s), tightening the delivery-trough logic. However, ongoing conversions (AMS11 27MW opened Nov 2025, FRA18 launch, new Amsterdam permit) confirm partial-slip rather than total-stall remains modal, so a modest upward adjustment to 0.45 is warranted without overstating a full Year-1 collapse.]"
}

